---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import FAQ from '../../components/FAQ.astro';
import { localizedPath } from '../../i18n/utils';

const locale = 'en';
const faq = [
  {
    question: 'What is the definition of the sunk cost fallacy?',
    answer:
      'A sunk cost is anything already spent that no choice can recover — money, time, effort. The fallacy is letting those unrecoverable outlays steer what you do next, like finishing a bad movie "because the ticket is paid." Rational decisions weigh only future costs and benefits; the sunk portion is mathematically irrelevant to every remaining option.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why do people fall for it?',
    answer:
      'Three drivers: loss aversion (admitting the loss hurts more than continuing), self-justification (quitting means the past you chose wrong), and waste aversion (abandoning something paid-for feels sinful). Knowing the drivers doesn\'t grant immunity, but it lets you name which one is pushing you in the moment.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I quickly test whether I\'m stuck in a sunk cost?',
    answer:
      'The zero-reset test: imagine you are meeting this choice for the first time — no ticket bought, no hours invested. Would you start it today? Yes → continuing is rational. No → the only thing holding you is the past, which offers no refunds. Ten seconds; works on subscriptions, courses, projects, and possessions.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How is this different from healthy persistence?',
    answer:
      'Check which direction the reasons point. Persistence cites the future ("three more months earns the license" — a concrete coming benefit); sunk cost cites the past ("I\'ve already put in two years"). Cross out every past-tense reason and see whether the remaining future-tense ones still carry the decision.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Are there exceptions where sunk costs should count?',
    answer:
      'Strictly none — spent money stays spent. Two near-exceptions: reputational commitment (quitting mid-promise damages relationships — but that\'s a future cost, not a sunk one), and deliberately using prepayment to bind yourself to the gym or the course — weaponizing the fallacy as a commitment device, which is fine when you know that\'s what you\'re doing.',
  },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="What Is the Sunk Cost Fallacy? How 'But I Already Paid' Makes Losses Grow"
  description="Sunk costs are unrecoverable; the fallacy is letting them hijack what you do next. The movie ticket, the buffet, the losing position, the two-year course — four scenes plus a ten-second zero-reset test."
  locale={locale}
  updated="2026-07-26"
>
  <p>
    <strong>Direct answer: a sunk cost is anything already spent that no
    future action can recover; the sunk cost fallacy is letting that
    unrecoverable past steer the choices still open — when rational
    decisions should weigh only future costs and benefits.</strong>
    Obvious on paper, and yet it may be daily life&rsquo;s most expensive
    thinking error, because it specializes in advising you to double down
    exactly when you are already losing.
  </p>

  <h2>The core idea: paid money has no vote on the next step</h2>
  <p>
    Thirty minutes into a movie, verdict certain: it&rsquo;s bad. The $15
    ticket is paid and non-refundable. The live options: (A) sit through
    90 more minutes, (B) leave and reclaim them. Notice:
    <strong>the $15 is gone under both options</strong> — it is sunk, and
    mathematically irrelevant to the choice. The only live variable is
    the 90 minutes. Yet most people pick A, &ldquo;because the
    ticket&rsquo;s paid&rdquo; — spending 90 real minutes to honor 15
    unrecoverable dollars. That is the fallacy&rsquo;s complete anatomy:
    <strong>because we lost, we add more.</strong>
  </p>

  <h2>Four everyday scenes</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>&ldquo;Getting my money&rsquo;s worth&rdquo; at the
      buffet.</strong> The $40 entry is paid; every plate from here costs
      zero. The correct way to &ldquo;break even&rdquo; is eating until
      satisfied, not until stuffed — each forced plate isn&rsquo;t
      reclaiming the ticket, it&rsquo;s paying the sunk $40 a second time
      in discomfort.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The unused membership.</strong> &ldquo;The annual fee is
      paid, wasting it would be a shame&rdquo; — the fee is sunk; the live
      question is whether each future visit is worth your future time.
      Regret retains no value; it only retains the charge. The audit
      method lives in <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/subscription-creep')}>subscription creep</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>&ldquo;If I sell now the loss becomes real.&rdquo;</strong>
      The paper loss is already real. Whether to hold should be decided by
      &ldquo;where is this money best placed today,&rdquo; independent of
      your entry price. This is the fallacy&rsquo;s most expensive arena —
      and this paragraph explains a bias only; it is not investment
      advice.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The two-year course, the half-done project.</strong>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve put in so much already&rdquo; — the two years are
      sunk. Zero-reset test: choosing fresh today, would you start this?
      Yes → continue (the reason lives in the future). No → the fastest
      stop-loss is now: year three isn&rsquo;t sunk yet, and it is the
      only thing still savable.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The ten-second tool: the zero-reset test</h2>
  <p>
    Facing any &ldquo;but I already…&rdquo; hesitation, ask:
    <strong>&ldquo;If I were meeting this choice for the first time — no
    money paid, no time invested — would I start it today?&rdquo;</strong>
    Yes → carry on; your reasons point forward. No → the only thing
    keeping you is the past, and the past issues no refunds. The
    test&rsquo;s power is physical: it deletes the sunk term from the
    equation, leaving only future terms — which is where
    <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/opportunity-cost-everyday')}>opportunity cost</a>
    takes over: every day you stay is a day of the next-best alternative
    foregone.
  </p>

  <h2>Why knowing isn&rsquo;t immunity: the three pushers</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Loss aversion:</strong> leaving converts the paper loss into an acknowledged one — acute pain; staying lets you keep pretending it hasn&rsquo;t happened.</li>
    <li><strong>Self-justification:</strong> quitting indicts your past self&rsquo;s judgment; continuing protects the past self — funded by the future one.</li>
    <li><strong>Waste aversion:</strong> we were raised not to waste. But the real waste isn&rsquo;t walking out — it&rsquo;s appending good time to a bad choice. The reversal worth memorizing: <strong>a stop-loss isn&rsquo;t waste completed; it&rsquo;s waste stopped.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <FAQ items={faq} />

  <p class="privacy-note">
    This article is general behavioral-economics education, not financial
    or investment advice; investment passages describe a cognitive bias
    only — consult licensed professionals for actual decisions. All
    calculators on this site run locally in your browser; nothing you
    enter is uploaded to any server.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>
